sentences: Afghanistan fought.
Showed a lot of spirit.
But sometimes it isn't all.
Sri Lanka were superior with the bat and Dilshan's experience came to the fore.
That's it from this game.
Tomorrow is a double header which will kick off with a mouth-watering Trans-Tasman clash in the mountains.
Hope to have you onboard for it.
See you!Mathews: "It was a much needed victory for us.
We haven't played well in the past.
Bowlers bowled well early on and then credit to Afghanistan batsmen for playing well.
The attitude in the practice games was superb and we just had to go out there and express ourselves.
We are not looking too far ahead.
Just want to take it game by game.
Can do wonders if we click as a unit.
"Stanikzai: "The total was  .
5 short.
And Dilshan played well.
Unfortunately we had  .
fielding lapses which cost us as well.
The pressure is there when playing big teams.
Hope we do well moving forward.
We have a message of thanks for the President as they sent our ministers and Parliament members to support us.
"Dilshan: "Two games and two ducks in the warmups.
Needed some runs and really happy that I was able to stay not out and finish it off.
was a good total, wicket was slow and the spinners found turn.
Later it became slightly easier with the dew factor.
They had quality bowlers but we batted well and the running between wickets was good.
Didn't try anything fancy in the first  .
5 overs.
Just looked to have partnerships.
When you come to these kind of tournaments, it's important to get runs in the first match.
Senior guys need to stand up and then youngsters can bat around us.
Looking forward to next game.
"Dilshan is Man of the MatchNeither are Afghanistan mere integers this World T20 nor have they braved  .
miles to be number-making gnomes.
Having motored to the Super 10s, they did start all intimidated but then recovered courtesy captain Stanikzai's fifty to post a par score.
In response, Sri Lanka hopped past Afghanistan's starting spin whammy and then Dilshan, the Dilscooping Dilshan of old, let loose.
The chase threatened to mutate into a mere formality until Afghanistan hit back with spin.
Nabi outfoxed Chandimal and Rashid Khan re-ridiculed his age to consume Thirimanne.
Dilshan's 56-ball 83 mocked a slow pitch and the match looked all but won when Mathews announced himself with a six.

The Afghan wheels then came off, the full tosses and misfields clawed back in and Sri Lanka strolled to a reassuring win.The players line up for handshakes and Dilshan is being heartily applauded by his teammates.
39-year old Tillakaratne Dilshan.
Still going strong .
Hamid to Dilshan, FOUR, and Dilshan finishes it.
Receives a full toss and buries it through mid-wicket before punching the air and bellowing in delight.
He's been brilliant on a night where Afghanistan put up a threatening score which could have proved as a banana skin .

Hamid to Dilshan, 2 runs, slices a yorker in front of third man and is on the lookout for two straightaway, Mathews is slow to take off and then has to really put the skates on as the throw is at his end .
Hamid to Mathews, 1 run, nudged to long-on .
Hamid to Dilshan, 1 run, very full on middle, whipped to long-on .
Hamid to Dilshan, FOUR, Afghanistan have slackened now.
Devoid of all belief.
Half-volley outside off, driven powerfully past extra-coverHamid Hassan [ .
is back into the attack .
Dawlat Zadran to Dilshan, 1 run, trademark Dilshan drive with front leg out of the frame, finds cover and scampers through.
The throw is at the striker's end where Mathews is gone but for a direct-hit .
Dawlat Zadran to Mathews, 1 run, follows him as he moves to leg with a very high full toss, Mathews uses the pace on it and steers it through the vacant point region.
Surprised that hasn't been called for height .
Dawlat Zadran to Mathews, FOUR, whips a low full toss wide of long-on.
Jeez, he's playing a blinder.
19 off 8 and has anything but sealed it .
Dawlat Zadran to Mathews, FOUR, oh another fielding lapse.
Mathews didn't deserve anything for that.

Jabbed at a back of a length delivery half-heartedly outside off, runs it off a thick outside edge fine of third man where Gulbadin makes good ground and slides but lets it pass despite getting a hand .
Dawlat Zadran to Mathews, wide, tries to catch him off-guard with a bumper but it's too short.
Sails over the half-crouched form of the Lankan skipper .
Dawlat Zadran to Mathews, no run, Mathews is in a spin here, worried that the ball might trickle back to the stumps.
Backs away and then chops a near yorker off the inside edge onto his body.
Imparts enough back spin that it veers away from the direction of the timber .
Dawlat Zadran to Dilshan, 1 run, full toss with a hint of reverse on off, Dilshan swings it to deep mid-wicketDawlat Zadran [ .
is back into the attackUseful couple of blows from the skipper.
How valuable is he in a run-chase!
Sri Lanka should walk this .
Rashid Khan to Mathews, FOUR, picks the googly which is dropped short, jumps back and pulverizes the pull.
Beats the diving deep mid-wicket fielder to his right .
Rashid Khan to Mathews, no run, way too wide outside off, and Mathews is still slogging to leg.
Turns away further and beats the bat by a distance.
Looked close on the wide actually .
Rashid Khan to Mathews, no run, tries an encore.
This one is the googly though.
Spins in and past the inside edge .
Rashid Khan to Mathews, SIX, Mathews breaks the tension.
It's Sri Lanka's game from here.
Moves across slightly before getting into position and slog-sweeps it over cow corner .
Rashid Khan to Dilshan, 1 run, flat-bats the drive wide of long-off and stays happy with a single .
Rashid Khan to Dilshan, no run, he's tried those reverse-swats more than once, and don't think he's fetched much from them.
Again mistimes it to backward pointRashid Khan [ .
is back into the attack .
Nabi to Dilshan, 1 run, very full outside off, drilled to deep point .
Nabi to Dilshan, FOUR, that's twice now that a shocking effort in the deep has converted a single into a boundary.
And both have been off full tosses.
Dilshan swings it behind square straight to the fielder who doesn't even get a hand.
And then cuts a puzzled figure .
Nabi to Dilshan, no run, he's focussing on bowling yorkers now.
Executes it well and contains Dilshan .
Nabi to Mathews, 1 run, facing his first ball, Mathews is offered a full toss and he only punches it to long-on .
Nabi to Dilshan, 1 run, another quick and full dart on the stumps, worked to long-onAngelo Mathews, right handed bat, comes to the crease .
Nabi to Dilshan, out Kapugedera Run Out!!
Now that's one way to do it.
Make the fellow at the non-striker's end pay for backing up too far.
No, don't worry.
No Mankad involved.
Dilshan squeezes it back down the pitch, and Nabi escorts the ball quite deliberately towards the stumps.
Kapugedara is well short.
Kapugedera run out (Nabi)  . )

!Mohammad Nabi [ .
is back into the attackFive overs left.
41 needed.
And with 7 wickets in hand, it should be a doddle from here especially if Dilshan stays there .
Hamid to Kapugedera, FOUR, once Kapugedera picks the slower ball, the rest of the task is too easy.
Sits up to be hit from a back of a length, and he slogs it over a leaping mid-wicket .
Hamid to Dilshan, 1 run, spears it into the blockhole just outside off, sliced wide of backward point .
Hamid to Kapugedera, 1 run, patted in front of backward point for a quick single and Dilshan makes his crease despite some stunning acrobatics from the fielder to effect a direct hit .
Hamid to Dilshan, 1 run, very full just outside off, Dilshan tries to drill it hard but squeezes it off the toe-end wide of cover .
Hamid to Dilshan, SIX, full toss and swiped away over deep mid-wicket.
Someone is caught napping in the crowd and is hit on the chest.
Ouch!
That man is rubbing his chest right now and seems to be okay .
Hamid to Kapugedera, 1 run, too close to play with a horizontal bat, tries to dab it into the off-side and chops it off an under-edge past leg-stump and in front of Shahzad.
Dilshan is desperate for strike and scampers through.
Direct hit might have been closeHamid Hassan [ .
is back into the attack .
Rashid Khan to Dilshan, FOUR, Rashid gets away with a juicy full toss.
Oh no, he doesn't.
Dilshan swung it straight to deep mid-wicket and the fielder lets it sneak through.
Inzi shakes his head in the dugout.
He should be having sympathy though given his glorified past on the field .
Rashid Khan to Kapugedera, 1 run, swept wide of long-on for a single .
Rashid Khan to Dilshan, 1 run, googly turning in from outside off, Dilshan hops to leg and punches to extra-cover .
Rashid Khan to Dilshan, no run, attempts a reverse slap to a quicker ball just outside off, skids on and past him before he knows it.
Had to be alert and not overbalance as Shahzad is waiting .
Rashid Khan to Kapugedera, 1 run, flatter on off, Kapugedera goes back and short-arm pulls it in front of deep mid-wicket.
The fielder has some ground to cover but the settle for the single .
Rashid Khan to Kapugedera, no run, generously tossed up, Kapugedera tries a massive slog-sweep from outside off, and is done in by the extra-bounceRashid Khan [ .
-1] is back into the attack .
Shenwari to Kapugedera, 1 run, oh so frustrating.
Glanced straight to short fine leg who fires an unnecessarily wide throw to beat the keeper .
Shenwari to Kapugedera, no run, quicker and fuller outside off, Kapugedera aims a cover-drive but the ball grips and skirts past his edge .
Shenwari to Dilshan, 1 run, tucks it through mid-wicket and then looks heaven-ward as a brilliant fifty is brought up.
Really, he has to be the one to carry them home .
Shenwari to Dilshan, FOUR, Shenwari has drawn the error but has to cruelly see a four against his name.
Drew Dilshan into a drive well away from the body, made him reach out and then found turn.
Dilshan goes hard and slices it between backward point and short third man .
Shenwari to Kapugedera, 1 run, sticks in the pitch from a shortish length on off, and Kapugedera's whip pops up in the air wide of long-on.
Landed well in front and wide of the fielderChamara Kapugedera, right handed bat, comes to the crease .
Shenwari to Dilshan, out T Perera Run Out!!
We have gone upstairs for a run-out check.
Dilshan misses with his pull down leg, or maybe gets some pad, and Shahzad fumbles too.
The ball doesn't ricochet very far from him though.
Still the batsmen are intent to sneak in a run.
Shahzad runs back, collects and fires the stumps down at the striker's end to find Perera's bat on the line.
T Perera run out (Mohammad Shahzad)  . )

Run Out!!
Nabi to Dilshan, 1 run, fires in a full toss and is flicked to deep mid-wicket .
Nabi to Dilshan, 2 runs, Dilshan is working this beautifully.
Keeping the run-rate in check and allowing Perera to do the teeing off business.
Softly clipped through square leg and an easy two .
Nabi to Dilshan, 2 runs, moves across the stumps to a ball which is anyway slipping down leg, runs it fine off the inside edge onto pad, and collects a brace before it's hounded down .
Nabi to T Perera, 1 run, sizes up the full dart and drills it to long-off .
Nabi to Dilshan, 1 run, plonks his leg across, and has to play round the front pad as Nabi kept it straight, flicks it through mid-wicket .

77 from 54.

Runs away .
Shenwari to Dilshan, 1 run, goes back and punches it to extra-cover who is at the edge of the circle .

is back into the attackLooks fairly even at this stage.

Afghanistan had run them close in the ODI World Cup last year, but the Lankan middle and lower middle order bailed them out.
This team doesn't have the experience of that one.
And Afghanistan won't make things any easy with their insurmountable spirit.
Inzi is out on the field having a chat with some of his boys.
Even the crowd has built up decently.
Stanikzai has plenty to say in the huddle.

We will fight hard in the field, it will be a good chase.
I was told to stay at the wicket, but this was a good wicket to bat on, I treated the bowling with merit, played the good ones and hit the bad ones.
Hopefully, we will win.
'Afghanistan have done exceptionally well to get a competitive total on the board.
They were jolted early when they lost their man in form Mohammad Shahzad, miscuing a pull to mid-on.
Despite a sedate start, Noor Ali Zadran and skipper Stanikzai kept the scorecard ticking before the old warhorse Rangana Herath struck in successive overs sending Zadran and Nabi back to the hutch.
But Afghan captain Stanikzai hung around for a steady fifty, he was slow to get going but once he found able company in Shenwari, he let loose.
Shenwari played a handy knock of 31.
It was Najibullah's hefty blows towards the end that gave Afghanistan the much needed impetus.
Even though he conceded 13 runs in his final over, Herath crafted a fine spell, kept deceiving the Afghan batsmen with his spin.
Chameera and Perera had a respectable outing.
Sri Lanka were sloppy in the field, dropping a couple of easy catches.
Can Afghanistan cause an upset?
We'll get to know in a few minutes.. .

Kulasekara to Najibullah, 2 runs, another full toss from Kulasekara, Zadran was swinging hard, lost his shape in the process, ends up slicing it high and over extra cover, comes back for the second run.
Afghanistan finish with  .
runs from the last 10 overs .

A slip in placeThe anthems are over, Sri Lanka complete their huddle and it's time for action as the two batsmen walk in..Afghanistan have cleared the qualification phase, it's now time for the main examination.
There aren't too many expectations from this bunch of happy-go-lucky bunch of players, but one or two upsets will delight the nation.
All to play for Sri Lanka, they haven't had the best of results in recent times, plenty of retirements and the replacements haven't been able to fill into their gigantic boots.

No Malinga tonight, that means the Afghan openers can breathe a little easy, they will not be facing toe-crushing yorkers first up.Teams:Sri Lanka (Playing XI): Tillakaratne Dilshan, Dinesh Chandimal(w), Lahiru Thirimanne, Chamara Kapugedera, Angelo Mathews(c), Milinda Siriwardana, Shehan Jayasuriya, Thisara Perera, Nuwan Kulasekara, Dushmantha Chameera, Rangana HerathAfghanistan (Playing XI): Mohammad Shahzad(w), Noor Ali Zadran, Asghar Stanikzai(c), Mohammad Nabi, Karim Sadiq, Samiullah Shenwari, Najibullah Zadran, Shafiqullah Shafiq, Rashid Khan, Dawlat Zadran, Hamid HassanMathews: "We're coming in as the underdogs and no pressure at all.
Guys are just looking to go out there and enjoy.
We want to improve in all 3 departments.
We haven't batted well recently.
Pitch looks to be on the dry side but I don't think it will change too much.
Don't mind chasing.
Senanayake misses out for Shehan Jayasuriya.
"Stanikzai: "We'll bat first.
Track looks slow, maybe will get drier after first innings.
We'll try our best in the tournament.

seats"The pitch was used in the match between Pakistan and Bangladesh.
Looks dry, cracks are obvious.
Could be a slow surface and hold a little bit for the spinners.
Hopefully under lights the cracks will lie down and close up.
Don't see a lot of pace in the pitch.
Could be a little two paced given some patchy areas.
Unless you bowl badly, can't see a high-scoring game," infers Ian Bishop at the pitch report.Prakash Govindasreenivasan, from the ground, tells us that Malinga is being put through the paces.
Bowling in the nets with a knee cap on.

Uncertainty still looms over whether he'll be risked for today.Deepu Narayanan, our stats editor, inputs me with this info.- Tillakaratne Dilshan's last four innings in India read 0, 1, 0 and 0.- Angelo Mathews has batted the most innings in T20Is without getting dismissed for a duck - 48!- Mohammed Shahzad needs one more six to become the first player from an associate nation to hit 50 sixes in T20Is.Meanwhile, Mohammad Shahzad and Mohammad Nabi have been key contributers to Afghanistan's success so far in the tournament.
While the former has been giving good starts to the side, the latter has been doing his part with both bat and ball.
Rashid Khan, the 17-year-old leg-spinner, has been impressive as well.
In this battle, it will be mainly down to how well the Afghanistani bowlers bowl to the Sri Lankan batsmen.
If they manage to keep the Lankans quiet, they can fancy their chances.The fact that they lost both their warm-up games, to Pakistan and New Zealand respectively, worsens things.
The knee injury to Lasith Malinga, their regular skipper, has hurt them badly and he remains a doubtful starter for this game as well.
The selectors were even forced to make a few last minute changes to the side with Lahiru Thirimanne and Suranga Lakmal being drafted in.
The side depends a lot on the experienced players, especially with the bat in hand, and that puts a bit of extra pressure on the likes of Tillakaratne Dilshan, Angelo Mathews and Dinesh Chandimal.
Can Sri Lanka leave the past behind and start afresh here?
Time will tell.Let's be fair.
Yes, Sri Lanka are one of the finest teams in international cricket, but they haven't played to their potential in recent times.
Angelo Mathews, stand-in skipper during the Asia Cup, himself hinted that people will have to be patient with their side, which is going through a transition period.
Their only win in the Asia Cup out of four games came against UAE, but even then, they only managed to scrape through.
Rewind a bit more, they even lost  .
to India in the 3-match T20I series.
Clearly, the build-up to this mega event has not been smooth.Afghanistan's impressive story continues.
They beat Scotland.
They beat Hong Kong.
They beat Zimbabwe.
Here they are in the Super 10 of the  .
World T20.
The Asghar Stanikzai-led side has been doing the right things and the results are showing.
Without being too optimistic, all they would want is a win in this round and a tough fight in every game.
Can they upset a side in their group?

Well, now that they are playing Sri Lanka, one might as well say that they have a golden opportunity to do so.Preview:

Sri Lanka arrive in India with a weakened side, at least on paper, and will find it tough to compete with some of the best.
Their form over the last few months is a telling tale of how far this Sri Lankan side has fallen behind in the absence of some of their best.
The defending champions are up against Afghanistan in their opening game, the team that has played an exciting brand of cricket and eager to pull off an upset or two.
Having won all their Group A matches to qualify for the Super 10s, Afghanistan have carried good momentum with them.
But the challenge will rise.
Even if they can't win any match from here on, they have the ability to put to display entertaining cricket.
Sri Lanka's biggest strength lies in the fact that despite being the defending champions they aren't carrying much expectations.
With the spotlight focused away from them, they can go out and play freely.
Much like the Indian team in the  .
edition of the tournament, they could spring a few surprises.
With Sri Lanka well aware of the fact that they aren't favourites to defend the title straight away, they are planning their course in the tournament one game at a time.
Angelo Mathews has stated, "Hopefully we can win a few games upfront in order to gain some momentum.
Once we get that, we will be very hard to beat."
Tillakaratne Dilshan is the senior-most member of the side.
Not only is he one of the most reliable bets in their brittle batting line-up, but also someone who has lifted his game in big tournaments.
He will have to play a massive role if Sri Lanka have to punch above their weight.
The likes of Dinesh Chandimal and skipper Mathews will also have important roles to play, while the bowlers need to be on the mark, going up against tough oppositions.
The Afghanistan team have a good pace attack, a couple of handy slower bowlers and a few match-winners with the bat.
If all the departments fire in sync, they can pose some serious threat to the bigger sides.
Having played three matches so far in the competition, they have a fair idea what to expect from the conditions.
Afghanistan have also trained in India at the Greater Noida Cricket Ground before the start of the tournament.
Familiarity of the Indian conditions and three back-to-back wins will give them some momentum ahead of the tournament.
